Why This Architecture?

CNN: sensor noise reduction + pattern extraction

BiLSTM: temporal degradation modeling

Attention: highlights failure-indicating timesteps

Dense: final RUL estimate

ğŸ›  Technical Highlights
Preprocessing

Sensor selection & normalization

Sliding window creation (W = 40 timesteps)

Train/Validation split via GroupShuffleSplit

Test windows generated per-unit

Training Strategy

Optimizer: Adam

Loss: MAE

EarlyStopping (patience=10)

ReduceLROnPlateau

Checkpointing per FD dataset

Evaluation Metrics

MAE (Mean Absolute Error)

RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error)

PHM Score (industry standard)

ğŸ“ˆ Final Model Performance
Test Performance Across CMAPSS Datasets
Dataset	MAE â†“	RMSE â†“	PHM Score â†“	Test Units
FD001	13.9	18.9	1337	100
FD002	28.2	39.1	394366	259
FD003	11.3	15.5	516	100
FD004	31.7	38.5	37499	248

These results come from the saved .keras checkpoints â€” no retraining required.

ğŸš€ How to Use This Repository
1. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

2. Launch Jupyter Notebook
jupyter notebook

3. Open:
notebooks/Engine Health Prediction - Tanvir.ipynb

4. Important notes:

Training is disabled by default

RUN_TRAINING = False


The notebook will load pretrained weights instantly

No GPU required for inference

